	<li>Millisecond precision</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple records with the same timestamp are okay</li>\r\n	<li>Gaps in data are okay. TSDB does not force you to store your data on an equally-spaced grid, like time series databases like <a href=\"http://www.sungard.com/fame\">FAME</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>A bunch of datatypes\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>32-bit integer</li>\r\n	<li>8-bit integer</li>\r\n	<li>64-bit double</li>\r\n	<li>1-byte character</li>\r\n	<li>64-bit timestamp (millisecond precision)</li>\r\n	<li>string (user-specified length)</li>\r\n	<li>date</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Intended usage</h2>\r\nTSDB is beta software, at best. You should <strong>not</strong> use it to store your only copy of some critical data. Its best use is to store a copy of your raw data in a format that makes it very easy to extract subsets. The idea is to write your time series model in a way that you pull subsets of your data into memory, do some processing, and then write the result to disc.\r\n<h2>Get the source code</h2>\r\nThe source code is hosted on Github. I\'m in the process of cleaning up this library, and right now only the C++ library is ready to use. I\'ve only tested the build instructions on a Mac (although Linux should be very similar).\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/afiedler/tsdb\">Get a copy of the source here</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/afiedler/tsdb/wiki/Build-Instructions-(Mac-OSX)\">Build instructions for Mac OS X are here</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Plans for this library</strong>\r\n\r\nAs time permits in the next few weeks, I hope to have this complete package cleaned up and ready to use. Here\'s what else have been developed and is in the process of being cleaned up:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>MATLAB and R libraries</li>\r\n	<li>A fast, optimized console application for importing delimited data from text files. This program also can filter text files (so you can split up a file containing different tickers into separate time series).</li>\r\n	<li>A console application to dump subsets of time series to text files</li>\r\n	<li>A GUI application that lets you make charts of your time series in view the raw data as tables</li>\r\n	<li>An example of how to write a C++ program to aggregate raw timeseries data to lower frequencies (minute or second data from millisecond data).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2></h2>','Time Series Database','','inherit','open','open','','53-revision-8','','','2012-06-23 12:51:40','2012-06-23 16:51:40','',53,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/53-revision-8-65/',0,'revision','',0),(164,1,'2012-07-06 17:19:10','2012-07-06 21:19:10','In this article, I\'ll show you how to use my <a title=\"Time Series Database\" href=\"http://andyfiedler.com/projects/time-series-database/\">Time Series Database</a> to import some sample U.S. equities data from <a href=\"http://www.tickdata.com\">TickData</a>, a data provider of high-frequency historical financial data. First, get the <a href=\"http://www.tickdata.com/downloads/SampleEquityData_US.zip\">sample data</a> and unzip it on your computer. Look in the Quotes folder for a file called GLP_27667.asc. This is file has quotes for Global Partners LP, a petroleum company. If you are running on Mac OS X or Linux, you can use the <code>head</code> command to see the first few lines, which in my download look like this:\r\n<pre>11/01/2011,04:00:00.301,P,14.5,21.36,5,1,R,,175,P,P,1,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,04:56:38.930,P,14.5,21.36,5,2,R,,18491,P,P,1,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,06:02:00.115,M,0,0,0,0,R,,40307,M,M,0,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:15:35.501,P,16.67,21.36,15,2,R,,73573,P,P,1,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:28:41.053,P,18.4,21.36,10,2,R,,80351,P,P,1,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:35:03.401,T,15.18,0,1,0,R,,88691,T,T,0,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:35:03.402,T,15.18,25.1,1,1,R,,88692,T,T,0,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:50:24.960,T,15.18,21.22,1,1,R,,100945,T,T,6,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:50:29.064,P,14.5,21.36,5,2,R,,100980,P,P,6,2,,C\r\n11/01/2011,07:50:29.072,T,0,21.22,0,1,R,,100981,T,T,6,2,,C</pre>\r\nIf you look on TickData\'s website, you can find a <a title=\"U.S. Equities TickData Format Definition\" href=\"http://www.tickdata.com/pdf/TickData_File_Format_Overview_US_Equities.pdf\">document describing the format</a> of these files in detail, but for this example, we\'re only going to look at the first 7 fields.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Date (MM/DD/YYYY)</li>\r\n	<li>Time</li>\r\n	<li>Exchange indicator (P means ARCA, M means Chicago, T means NASD)</li>\r\n	<li>Bid Price</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Price</li>\r\n	<li>Bid Amount (100 share lots)</li>\r\n	<li>Ask Amount (100 share lots)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLet\'s create a new TSDB file to store this data. To do this, use the tsdbcreate command.\r\n<pre>tsdbcreate glp.tsdb quotes char exchange double bid_price double ask_price int32 bid_size int32 ask_size</pre>\r\nThis command is creating a new tsdb database called glp.tsdb with a series called \"quotes\". That series has 5 columns: exchange (a character), bid_price (floating point double), ask_price (floating point double), bid_size and ask_size (both 32-bit integers).\r\n\r\nYou can add more than one series to a TSDB file. If you were to call the tsdbcreate command and glp.tsdb already existed, then it would add another series to the file.\r\n\r\nNow that you have an empty TSDB file, we\'ll create some import instructions and import the data. TSDB has a program called TSDB import that uses an XML file to describe how to parse the delimited data in a file like a CSV file and append it to the end of a time series.  Whenever you import data, you are always appending it to the end of a time series.<strong> </strong>You can import from more than one file into one series in a TSDB file, but you need to start with the earliest file. You also must make sure each of the files you import are in chronological order from oldest timestamp to newest (repeated timestamps are okay).\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example XML file that shows how you could import the TickData quotes files.\r\n<pre>&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\" ?&gt;\r\n   &lt;dataimport&gt;\r\n      &lt;delimparser field_delim=\",\"&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"_TDSB_timestamp\" type=\"timestamp\"\r\n            tokens=\"0,1\" format_string=\"%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S%F\" /&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"exchange\" type=\"char\" tokens=\"2\" /&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"bid_price\" type=\"double\" tokens=\"3\" /&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"ask_price\" type=\"double\" tokens=\"4\" /&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"bid_amount\" type=\"int32\" tokens=\"5\" /&gt;\r\n         &lt;fieldparser name=\"ask_amount\" type=\"int32\" tokens=\"6\" /&gt;\r\n      &lt;/delimparser&gt;\r\n   &lt;/dataimport&gt;</pre>\r\nThe XML import tells the tsdbimport command how to map the comma-separated values in each line into columns in the database. Notice in the timestamp <code>fieldparser</code> block, we specify to use tokens 0 and 1 to make the timestamp. This tells the parser to join tokens zero and one with a space and then to parse the combined string as a timestamp.\r\n\r\nYou can save that XML as a text file called \"instructions.xml\" and then import the GLP_27667.asc file like this:\r\n<pre>tsdbimport instructions.xml GLP_27667.asc glp.tsdb quotes</pre>\r\nAfter you run this command, you\'ll have the complete GLP time series imported. Now, you can access this data quickly via either the R or MATLAB TSDB bindings. Stay tuned for a article on how to do that within the next few days.','Using TSDB to store U.S. Equities data from TickData','','inherit','open','open','','85-revision-6','','','2012-07-06 17:19:10','2012-07-06 21:19:10','',85,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/85-revision-6-164/',0,'revision','',0),(67,1,'2012-06-25 12:18:07','2012-06-25 16:18:07','','Books','','publish','open','open','','books','','','2012-06-25 12:18:07','2012-06-25 16:18:07','',0,'http://andyfiedler.com/?page_id=67',0,'page','',0),(68,1,'2012-06-25 12:17:00','2012-06-25 16:17:00','','Books','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision','','','2012-06-25 12:17:00','2012-06-25 16:17:00','',67,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/67-revision-68/',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2012-06-25 12:17:52','2012-06-25 16:17:52','','Books','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision-2','','','2012-06-25 12:17:52','2012-06-25 16:17:52','',67,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/67-revision-2-69/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2012-07-05 22:33:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h2>The Personal MBA</h2>\nRead: July 2012\nRating:\n<h3>My Notes</h3>\n<h4>Introduction</h4>\nJosh (the author) wrote this book after reading a lot of other books on business, psychology, and marketing. He also has an undergraduate business degree and spent some time working at Proctor and Gamble. Honestly, I was a little skeptical that someone without a ton of experience (as a CEO or high-level executive) was qualified to write a book on business, but Josh does show a great ability to distill business problems and how to <em>think</em> about business problems down to some really clear and digestible writing.\n\nHe makes a few key points in the introduction that I think are worth noting. First, he repeats the increasingly common refrain that the MBA degree is less and less a smart investment. His main arguments against an MBA are:\n<ul>\n	<li>They are too expensive. Its not that they don\'t provide enough of a benefit, its that they cost too much for the benefits that they provide. This is pretty ironic, since cost-benefit analysis is one of the things they teach in business school!</li>\n	<li>They teach outdated methods. Business is changing rapidly, and MBA programs are focusing too much on complicated financial and statistical formulas without teaching how to improve a real operating business.</li>\n	<li>An MBA can\'t guarantee you a high-paying job, because the skills for high-paying jobs are learned by experience. An MBA can get you connection with recruiters, but actually getting the job is your responsibility.</li>\n</ul>\n<div>I tend to agree with Josh, so I didn\'t take note of too many of the finer points of his arguments. He does back them up with some studies and the arguments are well-reasoned, so if you are considering business school and are at all apprehensive, you should read it.</div>\nJosh also makes a good point about acquiring knowledge (learning). He\'s theory is that learning helps us to build better mental models because we are using the experiences of others to calibrate our understanding of the world. This book is a distillation of mental models Josh has learned from other business books, working at P&amp;G, and consulting.\n\n&nbsp;','The Personal MBA by Josh Kaufman','','draft','open','open','','','','','2012-07-05 22:33:30','2012-07-06 02:33:30','',67,'http://andyfiedler.com/?page_id=72',0,'page','',0),(73,1,'2012-07-05 21:46:15','2012-07-06 01:46:15','<h2>The Personal MBA</h2>\nRead: July 2012\nRating:\n\n&nbsp;','The Personal MBA by Josh Kaufman','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision','','','2012-07-05 21:46:15','2012-07-06 01:46:15','',72,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/72-revision-73/',0,'revision','',0),(74,1,'2012-07-05 21:54:50','2012-07-06 01:54:50','<h2>The Personal MBA</h2>\r\nRead: July 2012\r\nRating:\r\n<h3>My Notes</h3>\r\n<h4>Introduction</h4>\r\nThis','The Personal MBA by Josh Kaufman','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-2','','','2012-07-05 21:54:50','2012-07-06 01:54:50','',72,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/72-revision-2-74/',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2012-07-05 21:54:54','2012-07-06 01:54:54','<h2>The Personal MBA</h2>\r\nRead: July 2012\r\nRating:\r\n<h3>My Notes</h3>\r\n<h4>Introduction</h4>\r\nThis','The Personal MBA by Josh Kaufman','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-3','','','2012-07-05 21:54:54','2012-07-06 01:54:54','',72,'http://andyfiedler.com/blog/72-revision-3-75/',0,'revision','',0),(76,1,'2012-07-06 11:43:58','2012-07-06 15:43:58','<h2>Available for consulting</h2>\r\nI\'ve worked on a diverse array of projects, <a title=\"Conta